<body>
<h2>Loading and preprocessing the data</h2>

<p>We want to do a few things to clean this data:</p>

<ul>
<li>unzip</li>
<li>read as a csv</li>
<li>process the date column from character to Date-type data</li>
</ul>

<p>The data source can be downloaded <a href="https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/repdata%2Fdata%2Factivity.zip">here.</a> The pre-processing code is shown below.</p>

<pre><code class="r">unzip(&quot;activity.zip&quot;,exdir=&quot;./data&quot;)
out_file &lt;- &quot;./data/activity.csv&quot;
play_data &lt;- read.csv(out_file, header = TRUE, sep = &quot;,&quot;, na.strings=&quot;NA&quot;,stringsAsFactors=F)
play_data$date &lt;- as.Date(play_data$date, format = &quot;%Y-%m-%d&quot;)
</code></pre>

<p>Now the data is <em>cleaned up</em> and ready for analysis. Recall the data is comprised of three columns:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>steps:</strong> raw number of steps walked in a 5-minute interval. NA values exist.</li>
<li><strong>date:</strong> the year/month/day of the activity</li>
<li><strong>interval:</strong> a 5 minute interval from 00:00 to 23:55 in a 24-hour period</li>
</ul>

<h2>What is mean total number of steps taken per day?</h2>

<p>We must sum up the total number of steps taken per day, omitting any <code>NA</code> values in the denominator. For example, if there are 10 data points and 2 are <code>NA</code>, we would sum up 8 values and divide by 8 to get the sum. The <code>agregate</code> function allows us to do this. We summary steps by date.</p>

<pre><code class="r">steps_count &lt;- aggregate(steps ~ date,sum,data=play_data)
steps_mean&lt;- as.integer(mean(steps_count$steps))
steps_median&lt;-median(steps_count$steps)
print(paste(&quot;Mean steps per day:&quot;,steps_mean,&quot;Median steps per day:&quot;,steps_median))
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Mean steps per day: 10766 Median steps per day: 10765&quot;
</code></pre>

<p>Now that we know the mean (10766) and median (10765) values for steps <em>per day</em>, let&#39;s plot this data, with <code>steps_mean</code> to show the average steps <em>per day</em> taken. </p>

<pre><code class="r">par(mar=c(5,4,3,1),las=1)
hist(steps_count$steps, breaks=20,col=&quot;red&quot;,xlab=&quot;Total Steps in a day&quot;,
     ylab=&quot;Frequency of Days&quot;, main=&quot;Frequency of Total Steps&quot;)
rug(steps_count$steps)
abline(v = steps_mean, col = &quot;blue&quot;, lwd = 2)
text_x = steps_mean; text_y = 10
text(text_x, text_y, paste(&quot;Mean:&quot;,as.integer(steps_mean)), pos=2) 
</code></pre>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title="plot of chunk chunk3-plot1" alt="plot of chunk chunk3-plot1" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>

<h2>What is the average daily activity pattern?</h2>

<p>Average daily activity pattern means how many steps does one walk based on the time of the day (from <code>00:00</code> to <code>23:55</code>). Here, we are interested in averaging values based on a common <code>interval</code> factor, rather than a <code>date</code> factor. We will continue off the variables in the previous problem.</p>

<pre><code class="r">avgs_interval&lt;- aggregate(steps ~ interval,mean, data=play_data)
max_average_steps_interval &lt;- as.integer(max(avgs_interval$steps))
print(paste(&quot;Maximum average steps is:&quot;,max_average_steps_interval,&quot;at interval&quot;,
            avgs_interval[which(avgs_interval$steps==max(avgs_interval$steps)),1]))
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Maximum average steps is: 206 at interval 835&quot;
</code></pre>

<h2>Imputing missing values</h2>

<p>There are a number of <code>NA</code> values for steps. In fact, there are <strong>2304</strong> <code>NA</code> values. Let&#39;s make a new data set <code>clean_data</code> to play with. To clean the code, I chose a for-loop for ease of use.</p>

<pre><code class="r">clean_data &lt;- play_data
head(clean_data,6)
</code></pre>

<pre><code>##   steps       date interval
## 1    NA 2012-10-01        0
## 2    NA 2012-10-01        5
## 3    NA 2012-10-01       10
## 4    NA 2012-10-01       15
## 5    NA 2012-10-01       20
## 6    NA 2012-10-01       25
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="r"># Get the mean of steps by interval
tapp_avgs &lt;- tapply(play_data$steps,play_data$interval,mean,na.rm=TRUE)
# If NA exists, replace NA with mean value for current interval
for (i in 1:length(clean_data$steps)){
    if (is.na(clean_data[i,1])) {
        clean_data[i,1] &lt;- tapp_avgs[as.character(clean_data[i,3])]    
    }    
}
head(clean_data,6)
</code></pre>

<pre><code>##       steps       date interval
## 1 1.7169811 2012-10-01        0
## 2 0.3396226 2012-10-01        5
## 3 0.1320755 2012-10-01       10
## 4 0.1509434 2012-10-01       15
## 5 0.0754717 2012-10-01       20
## 6 2.0943396 2012-10-01       25
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="r"># how many NA&#39;s are left?
sum(is.na(clean_data))
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] 0
</code></pre>

<p>Now that we have cleaned the data and replaced <code>NA</code> values, let&#39;s plot again. For good measure, we will also show the differences.</p>

<pre><code class="r">par(mfrow=c(1,2))

clean_steps_count &lt;- aggregate(steps ~ date,sum,data=clean_data)
clean_steps_mean&lt;-as.integer(mean(clean_steps_count$steps)); clean_steps_median&lt;-as.integer(median(clean_steps_count$steps))

hist(clean_steps_count$steps, breaks=20,col=&quot;blue&quot;,xlab=&quot;Total Steps in a Day&quot;,
     ylab=&quot;Frequency of Days&quot;, main=&quot;Frequency of Total Steps\n with NA Replacement&quot;)
rug(clean_steps_count$steps)
abline(v=clean_steps_mean,col=&quot;red&quot;,lwd=2)


# show the old plot for a side-by-side comparison
hist(steps_count$steps, breaks=20,col=&quot;red&quot;,xlab=&quot;Total Steps in a Day&quot;,
     ylab=&quot;Frequency of Days&quot;, main=&quot;Frequency of Total Steps\n without NA Replacement&quot;)
rug(steps_count$steps)
abline(v = steps_mean, col = &quot;blue&quot;, lwd = 2)

<h2>Are there differences in activity patterns between weekdays and weekends?</h2>

<p>Using the clean_data dataset with no <code>NA</code> values left, let&#39;s see if the user is more active during the weekdays (Monday-Friday) or weekends! </p>

<pre><code class="r">clean_data$weekdays &lt;- weekdays(clean_data$date)
days &lt;- unique(clean_data$weekdays)
weekday &lt;- days[1:5]
weekend &lt;- days[6:7]

wkday &lt;- which(clean_data$weekdays %in% weekday)
wknd &lt;- which(clean_data$weekdays %in% weekend)
weekday_count &lt;- aggregate(steps ~ interval,mean,data=clean_data[wkday,])
weekday_count$wk &lt;- &quot;weekday&quot;
weekend_count &lt;- aggregate(steps ~ interval,mean,data=clean_data[wknd,])
weekend_count$wk &lt;- &quot;weekend&quot;
nw_data &lt;- rbind(weekday_count,weekend_count)

library(lattice)
xyplot( steps ~ interval | wk, data=nw_data,type=&quot;l&quot;,layout=c(2,1),
        at = seq(min(nw_data$interval),max(nw_data$interval),max(nw_data$interval)/20),
        main=&quot;Average Number of Steps Walked by Interval and Day Type&quot;)
</code></pre>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk chunk8-plot4"/> </p>

<p>So it looks like our person of interest is more active on the <strong>average</strong> weekend rather than the <strong>average</strong> weekday. By how much? Let&#39;s look!</p>

<pre><code class="r">diff &lt;- round(100*(sum(weekday_count$steps)-sum(weekend_count$steps))/sum(weekday_count$steps),
              digits=1)
print(paste(&quot;This person is&quot;,diff,&quot;percent less active on weekdays than weekends.&quot;))
</code></pre>
